				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=455145&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204570" alt="Petrograd" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=455145)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;" >Petrograd</a></span> <span class="odate time_1481895193 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">16 Dec 2016 13:33</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2710560">
									

<p>There's a few options there, but&#8230;</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>For the purposes of this article, I'd be willing to buy that the source of their power is their brains, but that wouldn't address things like differences in their strength of their abilities, aptitude with/control of said abilities, or differences in the abilities themselves.</p>
<p>This seems to be positing &quot;Catch 1x Bixby, insert into machine&quot; as if they're all more or less interchangeable, and the idea that there's a relatively non-limited supply of people out there with generic reality-bending powers at a standard level of power just isn't narratively interesting.</p>
<p>I'm pretty sure none of the reality benders in Foundation custody follow a perfectly identical pattern (i guess the witch is pretty similar to the superhero kid and that one guy who's a pile of organs, before he died anyway&#8230;), and people only tend to mention standard generic evil reality benders when they're giving somebody's tragic backstory.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>As for other origins for powers&#8230; on the wiki we've got young deities, humans who seem to naturally emanate alternate theories of magic, extradimensional fae with a literal Hume-storing magic organ, and a man who may or may not be God, all of whom are probably classed as reality benders.</p>
<p>You've also got two children who are developing into Bixbys with different levels and types of power and control (One in a coma, one who <em>should</em> be), and two deceased ones (One whose powers came out with dementia, one who cursed themselves to be a pile of organs). None of them exactly alike.</p>

							</div>

								
