					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/ghostpage" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2567302); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2567302&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204570" alt="ghostpage" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2567302)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/ghostpage" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2567302); return false;" >ghostpage</a></span> <span class="odate time_1481737793 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">14 Dec 2016 17:49</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2709431">
									

<p>I liked this! I liked it a lot.</p>
<p>My only nitpick is how does PL avoid scarring of the brain, as happens very often in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain%E2%80%93computer_interface#Invasive_BCIs">invasive brain-computer interfaces?</a><sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-534536-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-534536-1')">1</a></sup> I can't find any good sources on how long until brain scarring ruins the whole situation - I'd assume it depends on the specific equipment installed and the immune system/etc of the one with the brain shenanigans going on - but the efficiency of the ORI would deteriorate over time with potentially extremely varying times where they dip below an acceptable threshold.<br />
<sub>It wouldnt be me if I didn't find some kind of scientific writing lacking some obscure detail</sub></p>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-534536-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-534536-1')">1</a>. &quot;Because they lie in the grey matter, invasive devices produce the highest quality signals of BCI devices but are prone to scar-tissue build-up, causing the signal to become weaker, or even non-existent, as the body reacts to a foreign object in the brain.&quot;</div>
</div>

							</div>

								
					
